What sucks about getting over you is that in time we’re just going to go back to being strangers again. I feel like I’ve known you forever but it hasn’t even been a year yet. It’s sad knowing that what we were will be nothing more than a distant bittersweet memory that only we will know. It sucks knowing that we can’t go back to being friends anymore because going back will hurt me too much. I hate that you made me care about you more than I care about anyone else and myself. I miss the warmth and love that you gave me even if it was a lie you were telling yourself. You were the one person I was willing to be there for even during your worst times and I was…but you weren’t willing to let me be there for you and you didn’t even want to be there for yourself, but that’s my mistake for thinking you would have chosen the mature route. I’m frustrated that we acted so quickly on our relationship when I should have waited, this could have preserved our friendship. I hate that I think about you every damn day still but at least I’m not waking up depressed and with anxiety anymore. Thinking about you going back to the how you were before…going back to him…makes me sad because although we don’t speak anymore I still care for your well being and I know that you know that this isn’t what’s best for you. There’s a reason to why you will never get over him, and that’s because you don’t actually want to get over him. I have conflicting feelings about this, I hope that someday you will live a happy and healthy life but I also want to see you crash and burn. I wish I could have been proven wrong about you but everything I thought and everything that gave me anxiety about you turned out to be true. It’s quite the unfortunate but reassuring feeling when you know the things that gave you anxiety were true. It sucks because you werent just a lover, you were my closest friend and I think that breaking up with a best friend hurts far worse than breaking up with a lover. It sucks because you probably would prefer me to hate you rather than love you, and at this point I do hate you. You make me wish I never met you and I hate that you made me love you. Oprah coming in with that great advice. It seems so simple. Something that, in theory, should be so easy.  But it comes in direct opposition to that adage “Idle hands are the devil’s workshop.?This has been taken to mean that boredom is the work of the devil and that we must do everything our power to avoid idleness. I subscribed to this idea for a long time. I thought I needed to be constantly on the go, constantly involved in things, that I had to keep busy lest I should fall prey to sin and destruction. And I think that’s something a lot of parents are incorporating with their children these days - kids?schedules are so packed with activities that they hardly have time for anything else?which is often the point.   Learning to be still is something I’ve really been trying to do lately. I’ve been really quiet in my real life just because I’m trying to enjoy the fact that things are finally quiet and that I do have the opportunity to enjoy these moments. In that, one of my favorite bible verses keeps coming to mind: “The Lord will fight for you; you need only to be still.?(Exodus 14:14). One November 12 I wrote in my prayer journal what I felt like God was saying to me in that moment: “Be Still and Know.?And you know what I wrote in response? “Not particularly helpful but I’ll try.?Then on November 27 I felt like God was saying “Just Be Still.?Then the next day I was reminded of this verse in Exodus.   It really feels like this season of my life is focused on the idea of being still. It’s hard to undo years of feeling like I needed to fill every gap with an activity or a conversation. Being still can still be incredibly uncomfortable for me. But my entire spiritual life, both religiously and metaphysically, is pointing me back to this place. It’s time to take a break and just be still.   I never thought that I would ever find a way to love the stillness of life. I always ran away from it as if it were a disease that I might catch. But these days I find that I look forward to moments of doing nothing. I watch TV less, use the computer less after work, listen to music less, certainly have conversations less. It’s just one of those things I’m sitting into right now. I never knew how important being still was for the soul.  KTBSPA! -Lindsey

Ceci est mon tout premier article sur ce blog! Et que les choses soient claires dès le départ, je ne suis pas toujours en colère. Et je ne le serais pas toujours! Je vais utiliser ce Tumblr pour faire part de certaine de mes expériences, situations et communications en tant que jeune photographe auto-entrepreneuse récemment à compte. Et ça fait beaucoup de nouvelles choses.  Je ne sais pas si ce blog sera régulier, je pense poster lorsque j’aurais besoin de partager une opinion et très souvent un sentiment. Et aujourd’hui messieurs, mesdames? Aujourd’hui, je suis une photographe énervée - BJR, TARIF SVP  Pourquoi suis-je une photographe énervée? Eh bien à cause de Facebook. Cet outil indispensable pour tout entrepreneur débutant sans local pour accueillir ses clients. Eh oui! Car beaucoup entreprise même quasiment toutes créées après 2010 sont sur Facebook (Alors lâchez un like, ça aide, je vous jure!).  Malheureusement, ce réseau de tous les jours a ses failles?Et l’une d’entre elles sont la boîte mail/messenger. Attention, je ne parle néanmoins pas de l’algorithme ou quoi que ce soit d’autre! Facebook gère de ce côté! Je parle de certains clients?Ca me fait mal de le dire mais?JE NE SUIS PAS VOTRE MEILLEURE POTE! Pfiou, voilà, c’est dit.  Ce que j’entends par là c’est que, on ne commence pas une conversation avec un professionnel de n’importe quel métier?Même avec n’importe quelle personne en écrivant un simple “Bjr, tarif svp”?Mais tarif pour quoi? Pour qui? Des photos en extérieur, en studio? Pourquoi tu veux ces photos, pour un C.V.? Il y a tellement peu d’informations dans ce message! Et vous savez quoi! C’était pour un mariage! Mais dans ce cas-là, toute la journée? Où est-il? A 20 minutes de chez moi, à 3h de route? Puis-je dormir sur place? Et la plupart des personnages m’ayant envoyé un message pour des photos de mariage n’avaient même pas vu mon travail!!! Mmh?Ok? Je m’emballe mais?Lorsque tu vas chercher ton pain?Tu ne colles pas ton nez à la vitre en criant “TARIF SVP!? Tu rentres, tu regardes ce que la personne fait et à te proposer. Si tu veux un croissant et qu’il n’y en a plus tu poses la question à la vendeuse s’il en reste?Et bien c’est la même chose avec un photographe.  Les demandes de renseignements par Facebook ne me gênent en aucun point. Et c’est très agréable de savoir que notre travail plaît à ceux qui l’ont vu. Je suis vraiment super contente lorsque je reçois un message d’une personne qui me dit qu’elle aime beaucoup mes photos! :D Mais je ne pas répondre à vos questions si elles ne sont pas précise et?Je suis une personne, vous pouvez me parler et me répondre avec des phrases.  Ce qui nous amène au second point?NE PAS REPONDRE EST IMPOLI!  La majorité du temps, après une demande de tarif plus ou moins précise, je lui réponds en essayant de donner des détails sur le déroulement, le fait que j’essaye de personnaliser au plus chaque shooting pour que chaque personne se sente elle-même sur les photos. Mais zéro réponse, pas un merci, même pas un message expliquant que peut-être qu’ils n’ont pas les moyens pour le moment?Rien?Juste cette petite icône montrant leur photo de profil et indiquant qu’ils ont vu ton message?  Je vais de nouveau m’énerver et me répéter mais?Hey! Je suis un être humain derrière cet ordinateur!! C’est blessant de voir que notre message ne vos même pas la moindre réponse! Je comprends si cela est au-dessus de vos moyens, je comprends si vous estimer cela “trop cher pour des photos?(comme la plupart des gens le disent) mais, une réponse, une seule, je vous jure que je comprendrais.  Bon je crois que mon exutoire est terminé.  Je tiens à préciser que les images d’illustrations sont caricaturales et bien entendu fausses!     D’autres thèmes sont à venir! “On fait une collab?? “Vous êtes trop cher? “Je suis modèle”?Vous pouvez m’envoyer un message pour me dire lequel vous voulez lire par la suite!

Ultimately this reduces expected shock responses in the LA and blocks further learning)  The power of expectation can restrain hyper-emotional memories in the brain  The creaking of an opening gate followed by a dog attack can disturb otherwise pleasant evening walks. The sound of that gate opening on subsequent walks will elicit an emotional response, and the power of this response will be different if the dog was a German shepherd or a poodle. Through repeated experiences, the neighborhood, the gate and the dog all become part of the brain’s emotional memory system. The core of this system—the amygdala—forges indelible links of experience when we are attacked or threatened but, thanks to the power of expectation, the strength of these emotional memories is proportional to the unpleasantness of the experience.  “Forming an emotional memory is all about learning and calibrating our internal expectations with repeated external stimuli from the environment,?says Joshua Johansen, a team leader at the RIKEN Brain Science Institute. An instructive signal like a dog attack should startle you—and your amygdala—the first time it happens, but over time, both your brain activity and your behavior will temper the reaction to the dog attack once you learn to expect when and how it happens, for example on a particular street, outside of a particular house. In a study published in Nature Neuroscience, Johansen and colleagues discovered a neural circuit that can temper the strength of emotional memories by restraining the amygdala’s over-responsiveness to expected but unpleasant stimuli.  In the key experiment, rats were trained to learn the association between a mild shock and a preceding sound. The initially unexpected shocks strongly activated the lateral amygdala which, in turn, led to fearful freezing behavior in response to the sound. This freezing behavior increased with higher shock intensities, but once this association was learned, the shock-related activity in amygdala neurons diminished. “The first unpleasant experience sets off an ‘instructive?signal, which is gradually turned off as the amygdala learns to use the sound to predict the shock,?explains Johansen.  How neural circuits in the amygdala generate such 'predictions?to calibrate memory formation was unknown. The authors traced the origin of this modulation to a bundle of axons that leave the amygdala and flow into the PAG, a midbrain area that processes pain. There, the axons are well-positioned to dampen pain-related neural signals like shocks before they reach higher brain areas. The authors hypothesized that this circuit generates 'prediction error?signals that indicate how much an expectation differs from what actually happens, which are then used by the amygdala and other brain areas to set emotional memory strength and expectation levels.  If their idea was correct, then artificial inhibition of the amygdala-PAG circuit should interfere with normal prediction errors and expectations. Indeed, when they shut down a well-trained circuit, neurons in the lateral amygdala responded as if the shocks were being experienced for the first time. Johansen added, “By disrupting the circuit we deprive the amygdala of feedback, reset its learning level, and the shock memory becomes hyper-emotional, causing rats to freeze more.? The authors concluded that this neural circuit calibrates memory strength and helps the brain to form appropriate emotional memories. “We think that prediction-error signaling in such feedback-type neural circuits represents a general principle for brain learning systems,?says Johansen. “Because the feedback originates very early in the pain pathway, the nervous system can broadcast the prediction error to many brain areas like the amygdala, where it is then used to fine-tune memories.? Understanding this circuit may also shed light on what might go wrong when feedback is absent. “PTSD (post-traumatic stress disorder) is fear learning that has compounded over numerous exposures to bad experiences, like multiple tours of combat duty,?says Johansen. Such intense repeated activation of learning circuits could disturb normal prediction error signals in some individuals and make mildly aversive experiences seem much worse than they actually are. Human brain imaging studies on predicting unpleasant experiences indicate a related role for the PAG and amygdala. Johansen speculates that similar circuits that set memory strength based on prediction errors could perturb expectations in anxious people, a hypothesis deserving of further study.

🇫🇷📍 Paris 📍🇫🇷  Las leyendas de amor son ancestrales y no cesan de construirse. Sin embargo, la historia del puente de los candados de París, nos remonta a una leyenda reciente? Se cuenta que la tradición comenzó en este siglo, en Roma, en el Puente Milvio donde los enamorados ponen candados en las farolas. Sin embargo, pronto llegó a París, en los muchos puentes que tiene la ciudad. Pero sobre todo, uno de ellos, cuando se mira a lo lejos, parece un gran rectángulo dorado junto al rio Sena. El puente de París al que los enamorados van a poner los candados se llama Pasarela Léopold Sédar Senghor (también conocida como Pasarela de Solferino). Está justamente en frente del Museo D’Orsay, o el llamado Museo de los pintores impresionistas.  Esta usanza trata de venir a poner un candado en el Pont des Arts, sobre el río Sena, muchos de ellos trabajados con dibujos o con los nombres de los enamorados. I’ve come up with an idea on raising awareness to men’s mental health by making some Badfinger necklaces. Even back in the mid 1970’s, depression within men was serious. One of my favourite musicians had taken his own life because of very bad management of his band which left them penniless. 8 years later, his band mate did the same. Pete Ham & Tom Evans we’re incredible musicians and sadly, Pete never knew how good he actually was. Even George Harrison loved him, he was THAT good! I have decided to make these necklaces as a remembrance of Pete & Tom and show the world how incredible their band was. I have chosen the charity, CALM - Campaign Against Living Miserably which is a charity for men who has mental health issues which ends up suicidal. Pete’s story has really touched my heart massively and feel that I need to help in some way. Each necklace sold, at least HALF of the proceeds will be donated to this charity. If you have never heard of Badfinger, I urge you to go and listen. Pete & Tom wrote Without You which Nilsson went on and had a huge hit with. Fear is what usually keeps individuals from taking that dreaded first step not realizing once they’ve done it it opens up more opportunities to step outside the box to potentially achieve scarier goals. Some have a fear of heights (such as myself) and to overcome this fear is to do something that will move towards eliminating the terror one feels; for me it was zip lining.   The goal is to achieve the very thing that makes you cringe or brings you to tears just thinking about. DO IT ANYWAY! It may take a couple of times to muster up the nerve before going through with it but keep trying.  Once you achieve that very thing that stops you dead in your tracks you CAN achieve anything.
